Date:7/23/2011 12:02:26 PM
From:Ken Ludwig
EKS, Coastal lands, far from "marginal" in the sense I think you mean, are
often the brackish nurseries of many species and the home of the critical
organisms at the bottom of the food web. We already have seriously impacted
these most valuable areas of the planet with non-point source run-off from
large scale agriculture. It is in fact the largest polluter of our water.
Adding more nitrogen based fertilizer leads to algal blooms and they in turn
create hypoxic zones which kill all life. This occurs now in large areas of the
Gulf of Mexico from upstream effluent from the Mississippi and in the Great
Lakes, particularly Lake Erie.

The rate and volume of flushing and subsequent dilution of the Sea of Cortez
into the Pacific is unknown to me but does raise questions about Global
Seawater's ability to recycle enough of its production to avoid these kinds of
unintended consequences. I'll read up on them as soon as I can.

Figuring out these complex problems is precisely what we need to be doing and
we need to do it quickly. We also need to be smart about it. The binary nature
of the "discussion" about environment vs. capitalism is just stupid. We need
complex models and approaches and one of the optimal ways forward is to take
the best science, the best business practices, marry them to high standards of
ethical behavior and make a lot of money over a long period of time at good
margins.

All that said, I have followed your writing about Marine Harvest, looked at
their record and assessed their ability to both make money and behave
responsibly and invested accordingly. Market risk is high but so are growth a
opportunities and good margins. I agree enough in the growing need for protein
that I've committed substantial funds and will add to the food sector as high
risk/high reward opportunities present themselves.

Thanks for your many fine writings. I've learned a lot and earned a lot. best,
ken
